description.undefined:
The Change Detection Ontology (CDO) is used to capture information which relates the changes that have occured within the source data of an RDF dataset. 

The ontology allows a notification policy to be defined to notify users when a threshold of changes have occured. Once notified the mapping and source data should be re-examined to ensure no further action is required.

abstract.value: The Change Detection Ontology (CDO) provides a set of classes, properties, and restrictions that can be used to represent and interchange provenance and metadata information relating to changes that occur within source data that has created an RDF dataset. It can also be specialized to create new classes and properties to model provenance and metadata information for domain specific changes.

definition.value:
"Something that happened," as might be reported in a news article or
explained by a historian.

comment.en:
Note that, unlike some defintions of "event," this definition does not
specify that an event involves a change of state, nor does it attempt
to distinguish events from processes or states.

definition.value:
a named or relatively specified place that is where
an event happened.

comment.en:
This property relates an event to some meaningful place, which may
have a name (e.g. "Paris") or may be defined relative to some other
entity or entities (e.g. "the unincorporated area between Carson and
Harbor Gateway"). An event may be related to more than one such
place.

definition.value: an agent involved in an event.

comment.en:
This property relates an event to anything with agency, such as a
(legal or natural) person, a group, an organization, a computational
agent, etc. It does not imply any causal relationship, influence,
intentionality, etc.
